{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"065b81cb-b07d-45d3-896b-15b9fdf64f8a","content":"Here's what you need to do:\n\n1. **Update package references** in your `.csproj`:\n   ```xml\n   <!-- Remove -->\n   <PackageReference Include=\"xunit.runner.visualstudio\" Version=\"...\" />\n\n   <!-- Add -->\n   <PackageReference Include=\"xunit.runner.mtp\" Version=\"1.0.0\" />\n   ```\n\n2. **Add the MTP property** to your `.csproj` (or `Directory.Build.props`):\n   ```xml\n   <PropertyGroup>\n     <TestingPlatformDotNetTestSupport>true</TestingPlatformDotNetTestSupport>\n   </PropertyGroup>\n   ```\n\n3. **Run tests** the same way:\n   ```bash\n   dotnet test\n   ```\n   Or run the test project directly as an executable (MTP makes test projects self-contained apps):\n   ```bash\n   dotnet run --project YourTests.csproj -- --help\n   ```\n\n**Key notes:**\n- `xunit.runner.mtp` replaces `xunit.runner.visualstudio` — don't use both.\n- Keep your `xunit` (or `xunit.core` + `xunit.assert`) 2.9.3 packages as-is.\n- The `TestingPlatformDotNetTestSupport` property ensures `dotnet test` uses MTP instead of VSTest.\n- If you use a CI pipeline, verify it doesn't depend on VSTest-specific `.trx` output; MTP uses a different results format by default.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"73bf5f26-c3e5-4b84-b8f3-8ed378d2b946","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants to migrate their xUnit.net project from VSTest (using `xunit.runner.visualstudio`) to Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MTP). Let me provide a concise answer based on my knowledge of this migration path.","outputTokens":436,"requestId":"9821:97C07:16B74E:1D9920:69FFD7A8"},"id":"4116e05f-8a64-42c9-b1fc-08723afad068","timestamp":"2026-05-10T00:56:20.159Z","parentId":"e5a0862d-5f1b-4e14-8753-ea1b90693f15"}
